(Speaking Lesson) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Overview) Tj
T*
(Speaking builds confidence, fluency, and accuracy in oral communication.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Learning Objectives) Tj
T*
(- Explain the meaning of Speaking in English using accurate subject vocabulary.) Tj
T*
(- Describe the key ideas behind clarity, tone, structure, and audience engagement.) Tj
T*
(- Apply Speaking to examples such as presenting a short opinion with supporting reasons.) Tj
T*
(- Avoid common errors and build confidence through short presentations and oral) Tj
T*
(responses.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Main Lesson) Tj
T*
(1. Introduction To The Topic) Tj
T*
(Speaking builds confidence, fluency, and accuracy in oral communication. In a textbook) Tj
T*
(lesson, the first goal is to make the language idea clear. Students should be able to) Tj
T*
(explain what Speaking means, identify where it appears in English, and describe the main) Tj
T*
(purpose of the topic without relying on memorized sentences.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(2. Core Teaching) Tj
T*
(The central focus in Speaking is clarity, tone, structure, and audience engagement. This) Tj
T*
(means students must move beyond the overview and understand how the idea actually works.) Tj
T*
(A strong explanation should unpack the rules, relationships, or patterns behind Speaking) Tj
T*
(and show how those ideas guide correct answers. In English, success usually depends on) Tj
T*
(understanding the meaning, form, and effect that belong to the topic.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(3. How The Idea Is Applied) Tj
T*
(A useful way to teach Speaking is to connect the explanation directly to presenting a) Tj
T*
(short opinion with supporting reasons. That kind of language example shows students how) Tj
T*
(the topic moves from theory into use. At this stage, the learner should be able to state) Tj
T*
(the relevant rule or principle, explain why it fits the question, and then apply the) Tj
T*
(interpretation or writing method with confidence.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(4. Why Errors Happen) Tj
T*
(One common difficulty in Speaking is speaking without structure or clear transitions.) Tj
T*
(This matters because many learners can repeat a definition but still fail to use it) Tj
T*
(correctly. A real textbook lesson should therefore point out not only the correct) Tj
T*
(method, but also the exact place where students often go wrong. Learning improves when) Tj
T*
ET
